1
00:00:50,730 --> 00:00:54,564
SAGAN: Imagine that we are travelers
from the stars...

2
00:00:54,767 --> 00:00:57,099
...bound for the sun.

3
00:00:57,303 --> 00:01:02,240
We would discover it surrounded by
four giant, cloudy, gas worlds:

4
00:01:02,742 --> 00:01:06,269
Blue Neptune and its
frozen moon, Triton.

5
00:01:09,148 --> 00:01:13,346
And then farther in, Uranus
and its dark rings...

6
00:01:13,553 --> 00:01:16,852
...made perhaps of organic matter.

7
00:01:32,204 --> 00:01:36,766
Saturn, the jewel
of the solar system...

8
00:01:37,209 --> 00:01:41,111
...set within concentric rings...

9
00:01:41,314 --> 00:01:46,013
...composed of a billion icy moons.

10
00:01:57,797 --> 00:02:02,496
And finally, flanked by massive
satellites...

11
00:02:02,702 --> 00:02:06,001
...the largest planet, Jupiter.

12
00:02:06,472 --> 00:02:08,337
Its multicolored clouds...

13
00:02:08,541 --> 00:02:11,806
...studded with flashes of lightning.

14
00:02:16,782 --> 00:02:18,613
Still farther in...

15
00:02:18,985 --> 00:02:21,249
...closer to the sun...

16
00:02:21,621 --> 00:02:24,215
...there are no more
giant planets...

17
00:02:24,590 --> 00:02:27,957
...only a host of lesser worlds...

18
00:02:28,160 --> 00:02:30,492
...made of rock and metal...

19
00:02:30,696 --> 00:02:34,291
...some with a thin envelope of air.

20
00:02:34,500 --> 00:02:36,127
They huddle about the sun...

21
00:02:36,335 --> 00:02:39,600
...with almost no internal heat of
their own...

22
00:02:40,172 --> 00:02:43,471
...tiny places with solid surfaces...

23
00:02:43,676 --> 00:02:47,544
...one of which is a blue
and pretty world...

24
00:02:47,747 --> 00:02:49,305
...called Earth.

25
00:02:50,383 --> 00:02:52,010
Half-covered with clouds...

26
00:02:52,218 --> 00:02:54,277
...it is the home planet
of travelers...

27
00:02:54,487 --> 00:02:57,820
...who have just learned to sail
the sea of space...

28
00:02:58,157 --> 00:03:00,455
...to investigate close-up...

29
00:03:00,660 --> 00:03:03,356
...Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and
Neptune...

30
00:03:03,562 --> 00:03:08,329
...its brothers and sisters
in the family of the sun.

31
00:03:15,241 --> 00:03:18,733
Human voyages of exploration
to the outer solar system...

32
00:03:18,944 --> 00:03:23,210
...are controlled, so far, from a
single place on the planet Earth...

33
00:03:23,783 --> 00:03:25,444
...the Jet Propulsion Laboratory...

34
00:03:25,651 --> 00:03:28,211
...of the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration...

35
00:03:28,421 --> 00:03:30,981
...in Pasadena, California.

36
00:03:36,162 --> 00:03:40,121
Here on Sunday, July 8th, 1979...

37
00:03:40,332 --> 00:03:42,266
...the Voyager 2 spacecraft...

38
00:03:42,468 --> 00:03:45,926
...began its close passage
by Jupiter and its moons.

39
00:03:52,478 --> 00:03:53,968
General science systems...

40
00:03:54,180 --> 00:03:55,943
JPL MAN:
...are you ready with status check?

41
00:03:56,148 --> 00:03:57,206
Yes, I am.

42
00:03:57,583 --> 00:03:59,483
SAGAN:
The spacecraft had been instructed...

43
00:03:59,685 --> 00:04:01,448
...how to explore
the Jupiter system...

44
00:04:01,654 --> 00:04:03,622
...by a sequence of commands
radioed earlier...

45
00:04:03,823 --> 00:04:05,484
...to its onboard computers.

46
00:04:05,691 --> 00:04:07,625
Power, 450 watts.

47
00:04:07,893 --> 00:04:09,360
Power is go at this time.

48
00:04:09,562 --> 00:04:11,154
DSE systems.

49
00:04:14,767 --> 00:04:16,860
LACP mode is far and counter.

50
00:04:17,136 --> 00:04:18,967
We are at take 21 0.

51
00:04:19,171 --> 00:04:22,572
Direction last recorded was reversed,
and the track is track one.

52
00:04:22,775 --> 00:04:26,142
Here we check how faithful
an emissary Voyager is.

53
00:04:27,012 --> 00:04:28,946
Does it understand the commands?

54
00:04:29,148 --> 00:04:31,309
How is its health, its temperature...

55
00:04:31,584 --> 00:04:32,983
...its brains...

56
00:04:33,185 --> 00:04:34,174
...its heart?

57
00:04:35,087 --> 00:04:37,180
Yes, detailed science is coming up...

58
00:04:37,957 --> 00:04:39,822
"A" systems...

59
00:04:40,226 --> 00:04:42,160
...completed the status check...

60
00:04:42,361 --> 00:04:44,386
...and the spacecraft is go.

61
00:04:44,597 --> 00:04:45,586
Roger. Thank you.

62
00:04:45,798 --> 00:04:50,235
SAGAN: The modern ships that sail to
the planets are unmanned.

63
00:04:50,436 --> 00:04:52,165
They are beautifully constructed...

64
00:04:52,371 --> 00:04:55,636
...semi-intelligent robots.

65
00:04:56,242 --> 00:04:58,972
Voyager's eyes are
two television cameras...

66
00:04:59,178 --> 00:05:03,808
...designed to take many thousands
of pictures in the solar system.

67
00:05:04,016 --> 00:05:07,747
Along with other instruments, they are
mounted on a scan platform...

68
00:05:07,953 --> 00:05:10,615
...which points at passing planets.

69
00:05:10,990 --> 00:05:15,791
Voyager's brains are three integrated
computers set amidships.

70
00:05:15,995 --> 00:05:18,896
It communicates with Earth
through a radio antenna...

71
00:05:19,098 --> 00:05:21,032
...mounted like a sail.

72
00:05:21,233 --> 00:05:24,100
Voyager bears a message
for any alien civilization...

73
00:05:24,303 --> 00:05:27,795
...it may one day encounter
in interstellar space.

74
00:05:28,641 --> 00:05:33,010
Its louvers open and shut to help
control the onboard temperature.

75
00:05:34,180 --> 00:05:36,944
But Voyager cruises
so far from the sun...

76
00:05:37,149 --> 00:05:39,310
...that it cannot depend
on solar power.

77
00:05:39,518 --> 00:05:43,079
Instead, it has a small
nuclear power plant...

78
00:05:43,289 --> 00:05:46,417
...quarantined from the rest
of the ship.

79
00:05:55,901 --> 00:05:58,870
Many things can go wrong
in such pioneering missions.

80
00:05:59,338 --> 00:06:01,533
So people are a little uneasy...

81
00:06:01,740 --> 00:06:04,072
...at Voyager mission control.

82
00:06:04,476 --> 00:06:08,037
Jupiter is surrounded by a shell of
invisible but extremely dangerous...

83
00:06:08,247 --> 00:06:10,238
...high-energy charged particles.

84
00:06:10,950 --> 00:06:12,747
If Voyager flies too close...

85
00:06:12,952 --> 00:06:16,080
...its delicate electronics
will be fried.

86
00:06:16,288 --> 00:06:19,485
A collision with a small boulder
in the rings of Jupiter...

87
00:06:19,692 --> 00:06:22,855
...could send the spacecraft tumbling
wildly out of control...

88
00:06:23,062 --> 00:06:26,793
...its antenna unable to find
the Earth, its data lost forever.

89
00:06:32,004 --> 00:06:34,131
Voyager 1 and Voyager 2...

90
00:06:34,340 --> 00:06:38,436
...were launched a month apart
in late summer of 1977.

91
00:06:38,644 --> 00:06:40,942
After many alarms and close calls...

92
00:06:41,146 --> 00:06:44,877
...they successfully arrived months
apart at the Jupiter system...

93
00:06:45,084 --> 00:06:46,608
...where they worked brilliantly...

94
00:06:46,819 --> 00:06:49,686
...providing the first close-up views
of mighty Jupiter...

95
00:06:49,889 --> 00:06:52,722
...and its four large
and mysterious moons:

96
00:06:52,925 --> 00:06:56,554
Io, the innermost of the four...

97
00:06:57,096 --> 00:06:58,586
...Europa...

98
00:06:58,831 --> 00:07:02,096
...and moving away from Jupiter...

99
00:07:02,301 --> 00:07:03,768
...Ganymede...

100
00:07:05,170 --> 00:07:08,571
...and the outermost big moon...

101
00:07:08,774 --> 00:07:10,139
...Callisto.

102
00:07:11,844 --> 00:07:16,144
In a mission that costs
a penny a world...

103
00:07:16,348 --> 00:07:19,681
...for every human
on the planet Earth.

104
00:07:26,091 --> 00:07:28,355
Voyager's passage by Jupiter...

105
00:07:28,560 --> 00:07:31,757
...accelerated it towards
the planet Saturn.

106
00:07:31,964 --> 00:07:35,024
Saturn's gravity will
propel it on to Uranus...

107
00:07:35,234 --> 00:07:39,000
...and in this game of cosmic
billiards, after Uranus...

108
00:07:39,204 --> 00:07:43,402
...it will plunge on past Neptune,
leaving the solar system...

109
00:07:43,609 --> 00:07:46,009
...and becoming
an interstellar spacecraft...

110
00:07:46,211 --> 00:07:49,009
...destined to wander forever...

111
00:07:49,214 --> 00:07:51,808
...the great ocean between the stars.

112
00:07:52,017 --> 00:07:55,817
And if Voyager should,
sometime in its distant future...

113
00:07:56,021 --> 00:08:00,720
...encounter beings from
some other civilization in space...

114
00:08:00,926 --> 00:08:03,360
...it bears a message.

115
00:08:03,562 --> 00:08:07,430
A phonograph record.
Golden, delicate...

116
00:08:08,500 --> 00:08:10,195
...with instruction for use.

117
00:08:10,469 --> 00:08:15,099
And on this record are a sampling of
pictures, sounds, greetings...

118
00:08:15,741 --> 00:08:18,005
...and an hour and a half
of exquisite music...

119
00:08:18,210 --> 00:08:20,770
...the Earth's greatest hits.

120
00:08:20,980 --> 00:08:22,914
A gift across the cosmic ocean...

121
00:08:23,115 --> 00:08:27,279
...from one island of civilization
to another.

122
00:08:28,887 --> 00:08:32,015
The record bears in English...

123
00:08:32,224 --> 00:08:35,125
...an additional handwritten
greeting that says:

124
00:08:35,694 --> 00:08:40,427
"To the makers of music,
all worlds, all times."

125
00:08:40,733 --> 00:08:44,134
These voyages of exploration
and discovery...

126
00:08:44,503 --> 00:08:47,404
...are the latest in a long series
which have characterized...

127
00:08:47,606 --> 00:08:50,973
...and distinguished
the human species.

128
00:08:51,176 --> 00:08:53,406
In the 1 5th and 16th centuries...

129
00:08:53,612 --> 00:08:56,979
...you could travel from Spain
to the Azores in a few days.

130
00:08:57,182 --> 00:09:00,151
The same time it takes now
to cross that little channel...

131
00:09:00,352 --> 00:09:02,411
...from the Earth to the moon.

132
00:09:03,422 --> 00:09:06,789
It took, then, a few months
to traverse the Atlantic Ocean...

133
00:09:06,992 --> 00:09:09,654
...and reach what was called
the "New World"...

134
00:09:09,862 --> 00:09:10,851
...the Americas.

135
00:09:11,063 --> 00:09:14,829
Today it takes a few months
to cross the inner solar system...

136
00:09:15,034 --> 00:09:18,094
...and reach Mars and Venus,
truly and literally...

137
00:09:18,303 --> 00:09:20,498
...new worlds awaiting us.

138
00:09:21,840 --> 00:09:23,637
In the 1 7th and 18th centuries...

139
00:09:23,842 --> 00:09:28,074
...you could travel from Holland
to China, say, in a year or two...

140
00:09:28,280 --> 00:09:30,339
...the same time
it takes now for Voyager...

141
00:09:30,549 --> 00:09:32,949
...to travel from the Earth
to Jupiter.

142
00:09:36,722 --> 00:09:40,214
And in comparison to the resources
of the society...

143
00:09:40,426 --> 00:09:43,759
...it cost more then to send
sailing ships to the Far East...

144
00:09:43,962 --> 00:09:47,489
...than it does now
to send spaceships to the planets.

145
00:09:51,236 --> 00:09:53,227
The passion to explore...

146
00:09:53,439 --> 00:09:55,771
...is at the heart of being human.

147
00:09:55,974 --> 00:09:58,704
This impulse to go,
to see, to know...

148
00:09:58,911 --> 00:10:01,436
...has found expression
in every culture.

149
00:10:03,182 --> 00:10:06,640
Africa was circumnavigated
by Phoenician sailors...

150
00:10:06,852 --> 00:10:09,446
...in the employ
of an Egyptian pharaoh...

151
00:10:09,655 --> 00:10:12,681
...in the 7th century B.C.

152
00:10:13,959 --> 00:10:16,393
The islands of the Pacific
were settled...

153
00:10:16,595 --> 00:10:20,031
...by skilled and heroic navigators
from Indonesia.

154
00:10:21,500 --> 00:10:24,094
Great fleets of ocean-going junks...

155
00:10:24,303 --> 00:10:27,170
...left the ports
of Ming Dynasty China...

156
00:10:27,372 --> 00:10:30,136
...to explore India and Africa.

157
00:10:30,843 --> 00:10:33,539
A century later,
three ships left Spain...

158
00:10:33,745 --> 00:10:36,111
...under the command
of an Italian navigator...

159
00:10:36,315 --> 00:10:38,408
...to discover the Americas.

160
00:10:39,284 --> 00:10:42,151
And then a Portuguese
expedition succeeded...

161
00:10:42,354 --> 00:10:45,983
...in sailing all the way
around this blue globe.

162
00:10:47,426 --> 00:10:50,020
These voyagers of many cultures...

163
00:10:50,229 --> 00:10:52,891
...were the first planetary explorers.

164
00:10:53,098 --> 00:10:56,192
They have bound the Earth up
into one world.

165
00:10:56,401 --> 00:10:58,460
In our exploration
of other worlds...

166
00:10:58,670 --> 00:11:01,298
...we follow in their footsteps.

167
00:11:03,408 --> 00:11:06,468
Our present spaceships
are the harbingers...

168
00:11:06,678 --> 00:11:11,615
...the vanguard of future human
expeditions to the planets.

169
00:11:12,217 --> 00:11:15,186
We have traveled this way before...

170
00:11:15,387 --> 00:11:18,550
...and there is much to be learned...

171
00:11:18,757 --> 00:11:22,659
...by studying those great voyages of
a few centuries ago.

172
00:11:36,808 --> 00:11:38,366
In the 1 7th century...

173
00:11:38,577 --> 00:11:41,045
...the citizens of the new Dutch
Republic...

174
00:11:41,246 --> 00:11:45,808
...pursued a course of vigorous
planetary exploration.

175
00:11:47,486 --> 00:11:49,886
Holland was then
a revolutionary society.

176
00:11:50,088 --> 00:11:53,057
It had just declared its
independence from the powerful...

177
00:11:53,258 --> 00:11:55,249
...but stagnant Spanish empire...

178
00:11:55,460 --> 00:11:57,655
...and with a newfound
self-confidence...

179
00:11:57,863 --> 00:12:00,798
...Holland embraced, more fully than
any other nation of its time...

180
00:12:00,999 --> 00:12:04,457
...the spirit of the European
Enlightenment.

181
00:12:09,208 --> 00:12:12,837
It was a rational, orderly
and creative society.

182
00:12:13,045 --> 00:12:16,446
But because Spanish ports and vessels
were closed to the Dutch...

183
00:12:16,648 --> 00:12:18,809
...the economic survival
of the tiny republic...

184
00:12:19,017 --> 00:12:23,249
...depended on its ability to
construct, man and operate...

185
00:12:23,455 --> 00:12:26,185
...a great fleet of commercial
sailing vessels.

186
00:12:30,495 --> 00:12:32,326
The Dutch East India Company...

187
00:12:32,531 --> 00:12:35,625
...was a combined governmental
and commercial enterprise...

188
00:12:35,834 --> 00:12:38,462
...which sent shipping
to the far corners of the world...

189
00:12:38,670 --> 00:12:43,164
...to acquire rare commodities and
resell them at a profit in Europe.

190
00:12:43,375 --> 00:12:46,970
Such voyages were the life's blood
of the republic.

191
00:12:50,949 --> 00:12:55,181
Navigational charts and maps
were classified as state secrets.

192
00:12:55,554 --> 00:12:58,682
Ships sometimes left
with sealed sailing orders...

193
00:12:58,890 --> 00:13:01,882
...the crews embarking
for an unknown destination...

194
00:13:02,094 --> 00:13:05,894
...more than a year away
on the far side of the planet.

195
00:13:08,734 --> 00:13:11,999
These expeditions were not only
commercial exploitations...

196
00:13:12,204 --> 00:13:14,263
...although there was certainly
plenty of that.

197
00:13:14,473 --> 00:13:17,704
Beside the usual appeals
of ambition, greed...

198
00:13:17,909 --> 00:13:20,639
...national pride
and the thirst for adventure...

199
00:13:21,013 --> 00:13:24,847
...the Dutch were also motivated
by a powerful scientific curiosity...

200
00:13:25,050 --> 00:13:27,678
...and a fascination with
all things new.

201
00:13:27,886 --> 00:13:30,821
New lands, new peoples...

202
00:13:31,023 --> 00:13:32,650
...new plants and animals.

203
00:13:38,330 --> 00:13:41,731
This building,
then the Amsterdam town hall...

204
00:13:41,933 --> 00:13:45,061
...still attests
to the hardy self-assurance...

205
00:13:45,270 --> 00:13:47,204
...of its 1 7th-century architects.

206
00:13:47,406 --> 00:13:50,864
Its lavish crystal adornments
still reflect...

207
00:13:51,076 --> 00:13:54,068
...the glittering pride they felt
in their accomplishments...

208
00:13:54,279 --> 00:13:55,712
...and their prosperity.

209
00:13:55,914 --> 00:13:59,315
It took shiploads of marble
to build this place.

210
00:13:59,518 --> 00:14:03,614
Constantin Huygens, a poet
and diplomat of the time...

211
00:14:03,822 --> 00:14:07,280
...said that this town hall
dispelled what he called...

212
00:14:07,492 --> 00:14:10,859
..."the Gothic squint and squalor."

213
00:14:12,664 --> 00:14:17,499
The Middle Ages had ended,
the Enlightenment had begun.

214
00:14:21,073 --> 00:14:23,303
Up there, do you see...

215
00:14:23,508 --> 00:14:27,945
...is Atlas supporting the heavens
on his shoulders.

216
00:14:28,547 --> 00:14:30,174
And beneath...

217
00:14:31,616 --> 00:14:34,585
...is Justice with a golden sword...

218
00:14:34,786 --> 00:14:37,448
...and golden scales flanked...

219
00:14:38,390 --> 00:14:41,450
...by Death and Punishment.

220
00:14:41,960 --> 00:14:46,158
And who is it that Justice
is trampling underfoot?

221
00:14:46,365 --> 00:14:50,734
Why, it's Avarice and Envy...

222
00:14:50,936 --> 00:14:53,666
...the gods of the merchants.

223
00:14:53,872 --> 00:14:57,933
The Dutch knew that the unrestrained
pursuit of profit...

224
00:14:58,143 --> 00:15:01,874
...posed serious threats
to the soul of the nation.

225
00:15:03,081 --> 00:15:05,549
A less allegorical symbol...

226
00:15:05,751 --> 00:15:08,447
...is down here, on the floor.

227
00:15:11,757 --> 00:15:14,954
It is a great inlaid map...

228
00:15:15,160 --> 00:15:19,859
...stretching from West Africa
to the Pacific Ocean.

229
00:15:20,065 --> 00:15:23,933
The whole world was then
Holland's arena.

230
00:15:25,470 --> 00:15:28,337
In a typical year, many sailing
vessels...

231
00:15:28,540 --> 00:15:31,839
...set out halfway around the world
for the Far East...

232
00:15:32,043 --> 00:15:36,104
...on voyages of exploration
and discovery, of trade...

233
00:15:36,314 --> 00:15:39,112
...journeys taking years
to accomplish.

234
00:15:39,317 --> 00:15:43,276
Down the west coast of Africa, through
what they called the Ethiopian sea...

235
00:15:43,488 --> 00:15:46,286
...skirting the southern coast
of Africa...

236
00:15:46,491 --> 00:15:49,221
...through the Straits
of Madagascar...

237
00:15:49,428 --> 00:15:53,228
...and on past the southern tip
of India...

238
00:15:53,432 --> 00:15:58,335
...to the Spice Islands
and present-day Indonesia.

239
00:16:03,442 --> 00:16:07,037
Another set of voyages went south
then east, to New Holland...

240
00:16:07,245 --> 00:16:09,770
...later renamed Australia.

241
00:16:15,320 --> 00:16:19,381
And still other journeys ventured
through the Straits of Malacca...

242
00:16:19,858 --> 00:16:22,486
...to the Empire of China.

243
00:16:24,129 --> 00:16:28,998
But Holland was a small country
forced to live by its wits.

244
00:16:29,201 --> 00:16:31,897
There was a strong pacifist element
in its foreign policy.

245
00:16:32,704 --> 00:16:36,435
Never before or since
has Holland boasted such a galaxy...

246
00:16:36,641 --> 00:16:40,338
...of scientists, mathematicians,
philosophers and artists.

247
00:16:42,347 --> 00:16:45,783
This was the time of the great
painters, Rembrandt...

248
