00:33:29,220 --> 00:33:30,847
...dodoes...

497
00:33:31,355 --> 00:33:33,414
...rhinos...

498
00:33:33,924 --> 00:33:35,448
...leopards...

499
00:33:35,659 --> 00:33:38,924
...and other creatures.

500
00:33:41,732 --> 00:33:46,328
Modern voyagers
also return travelers' tales:

501
00:33:46,670 --> 00:33:51,607
Tales of a world shattered
like a crystal sphere.

502
00:33:52,376 --> 00:33:54,867
A place where the ground is covered...

503
00:33:55,079 --> 00:33:59,641
...with what looks like
a network of giant cobwebs.

504
00:34:03,020 --> 00:34:06,080
A world with an underground ocean.

505
00:34:07,424 --> 00:34:10,359
Tiny moons shaped like potatoes.

506
00:34:11,762 --> 00:34:14,458
A yellow and red pockmarked land...

507
00:34:14,665 --> 00:34:16,496
...with lakes of molten sulfur...

508
00:34:16,700 --> 00:34:20,693
...and volcanic eruptions
300 kilometers high.

509
00:34:24,475 --> 00:34:26,102
And a place called Jupiter...

510
00:34:26,310 --> 00:34:29,643
...so large that a thousand Earths
would fit inside.

511
00:34:29,847 --> 00:34:33,078
There are no mountains, valleys,
volcanoes or rivers there.

512
00:34:33,284 --> 00:34:36,014
Just a vast ocean of gas and clouds.

513
00:34:36,220 --> 00:34:39,883
Everything we see on Jupiter
is floating in the sky.

514
00:34:42,960 --> 00:34:46,293
But there's much that is fascinating
about Jupiter.

515
00:34:46,630 --> 00:34:50,066
As the solar system condensed
out of interstellar gas and dust...

516
00:34:50,267 --> 00:34:54,704
...Jupiter acquired most of the matter
not ejected into interstellar space...

517
00:34:54,905 --> 00:34:58,204
...and which didn't fall inwards
to form the sun.

518
00:34:58,409 --> 00:35:03,312
Jupiter is made mostly of hydrogen
and helium, just like the sun...

519
00:35:03,514 --> 00:35:08,110
...and had Jupiter been a few dozen
times more massive...

520
00:35:08,319 --> 00:35:09,786
...the matter in it...

521
00:35:09,987 --> 00:35:14,424
...might have undergone thermonuclear
reactions in the interior...

522
00:35:14,625 --> 00:35:18,857
...and Jupiter would have begun
to shine by its own light.

523
00:35:19,063 --> 00:35:23,056
Jupiter is a star that failed.

524
00:35:23,400 --> 00:35:24,799
Had it become a star...

525
00:35:25,002 --> 00:35:27,562
...we would be living
in a double-star system...

526
00:35:27,771 --> 00:35:29,864
...with two suns in our sky...

527
00:35:30,074 --> 00:35:33,737
...and the nights
would come more rarely.

528
00:35:33,944 --> 00:35:38,040
Deep below the clouds of Jupiter, the
weights of the layers of atmosphere...

529
00:35:38,248 --> 00:35:41,115
...produce pressures
which are much greater...

530
00:35:41,318 --> 00:35:44,116
...than any that are found
anywhere on the Earth.

531
00:35:44,355 --> 00:35:46,255
The clouds are this layer here.

532
00:35:46,457 --> 00:35:49,517
The deep interior
is this high-pressure place.

533
00:35:49,727 --> 00:35:51,354
The pressure is so large...

534
00:35:51,562 --> 00:35:56,090
...that electrons are squeezed off
hydrogen atoms, producing...

535
00:35:57,101 --> 00:36:01,162
...liquid metallic hydrogen.

536
00:36:01,472 --> 00:36:06,171
But at the very core of Jupiter,
there may be a lump...

537
00:36:06,377 --> 00:36:07,435
...of rock and iron...

538
00:36:07,645 --> 00:36:12,082
...a giant Earth-like world
under astonishing pressures...

539
00:36:12,282 --> 00:36:16,912
...hidden forever at the center
of the largest planet.

540
00:36:19,223 --> 00:36:20,690
Just before Voyager...

541
00:36:20,891 --> 00:36:25,658
...encountered Jupiter, you could see
that giant planet at night...

542
00:36:25,863 --> 00:36:30,800
...shining in the sky as our ancestors
have for the last million years.

543
00:36:31,101 --> 00:36:33,831
And on my way to study
the Voyager data...

544
00:36:34,038 --> 00:36:36,506
...arriving at the
Jet Propulsion Laboratory...

545
00:36:36,707 --> 00:36:39,801
...I thought that Jupiter
would never be the same again.

546
00:36:40,010 --> 00:36:43,969
Never again just a point of light
in the night sky...

547
00:36:44,181 --> 00:36:48,515
...but forever after, a place
to be explored and known.

548
00:36:51,655 --> 00:36:56,183
To see the first close-up images
of a world never before known...

549
00:36:56,393 --> 00:37:00,591
...is a great joy in the life
of a planetary scientist.

550
00:37:02,833 --> 00:37:07,236
In the early morning hours of
July 9th, 1979, on the real-time...

551
00:37:07,438 --> 00:37:10,407
...television monitors at the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory...

552
00:37:10,607 --> 00:37:13,735
...we began to learn
about a world called Europa.

553
00:37:13,977 --> 00:37:16,036
These are the modern explorers.

554
00:37:16,246 --> 00:37:17,975
Men and women trained...

555
00:37:18,182 --> 00:37:21,117
...in astronomy, physics,
geology or engineering.

556
00:37:21,318 --> 00:37:24,287
Many devoting five to eight years
to this single mission.

557
00:37:24,488 --> 00:37:28,049
JPL MAN: Cassen's model for Europa
says if you start with a liquid...

558
00:37:28,258 --> 00:37:31,022
...you can put in enough energy
to keep it liquid.

559
00:37:32,429 --> 00:37:36,490
But Cassen said in order for there
to be enough heating going on...

560
00:37:36,700 --> 00:37:40,932
...you had to start the heating
before Europa basically cooled off.

561
00:37:42,339 --> 00:37:44,671
But what about relief
from the cracks?

562
00:37:47,845 --> 00:37:51,679
...and Europa there's a twin,
a pair there...

563
00:37:52,683 --> 00:37:56,016
You can't look at a world
so different from ours...

564
00:37:56,220 --> 00:37:58,279
...without wondering
how both were made.

565
00:37:58,489 --> 00:38:00,514
Just rotate it out a little bit.

566
00:38:01,959 --> 00:38:05,827
Voyager presented us with six new
worlds in the Jupiter system alone.

567
00:38:06,797 --> 00:38:10,858
The more you learn about other worlds,
the better you understand our own.

568
00:38:11,068 --> 00:38:16,005
We speculate, criticize, argue,
calculate, reflect and wonder.

569
00:38:16,340 --> 00:38:20,106
We return again to the astonishing
data, and slowly...

570
00:38:20,310 --> 00:38:22,676
...we begin to understand.

571
00:38:33,757 --> 00:38:37,124
The Dutch sailing ships brought back
rare and valuable commodities...

572
00:38:37,327 --> 00:38:39,318
...from the new worlds they visited.

573
00:38:39,530 --> 00:38:41,464
Our Voyager spaceships...

574
00:38:41,665 --> 00:38:44,327
...return rare and valuable
information...

575
00:38:44,535 --> 00:38:48,266
...to computerized wharves on this
shore of the sea of space.

576
00:38:49,039 --> 00:38:53,942
Here the data are stored,
enhanced, processed and treasured.

577
00:38:54,645 --> 00:38:58,240
Maps of alien lands will be generated
from this information.

578
00:38:58,448 --> 00:39:02,544
In this electric warehouse
are tens of thousands of images...

579
00:39:02,753 --> 00:39:05,586
...of previously unknown worlds.

580
00:39:07,758 --> 00:39:11,159
How does a picture from
the outer solar system get to us?

581
00:39:11,361 --> 00:39:14,728
Sunlight shines on Europa,
and is reflected back to space...

582
00:39:14,932 --> 00:39:16,763
...where some strikes the phosphors...

583
00:39:16,967 --> 00:39:20,232
...of the Voyager television cameras,
generating an image.

584
00:39:20,437 --> 00:39:23,668
The image is radioed back
across the immense distance...

585
00:39:23,874 --> 00:39:26,035
...of half a billion kilometers...

586
00:39:26,243 --> 00:39:29,440
...to a radio telescope on Earth.
One in Australia, say.

587
00:39:29,646 --> 00:39:32,410
The telescope then passes
the information...

588
00:39:32,616 --> 00:39:35,608
...via communications satellite
in Earth orbit...

589
00:39:35,819 --> 00:39:37,514
...to Southern California.

590
00:39:37,721 --> 00:39:41,680
There, it's transmitted
by a set of microwave relay towers...

591
00:39:41,892 --> 00:39:45,259
...to a computer
at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory...

592
00:39:46,096 --> 00:39:48,997
...and there it is processed.

593
00:39:56,273 --> 00:39:58,867
The picture is like
a newspaper wire photo...

594
00:39:59,076 --> 00:40:02,978
...made of a million individual dots
of differing shades of gray...

595
00:40:03,180 --> 00:40:05,910
...so fine and close together
that at a distance...

596
00:40:06,116 --> 00:40:08,949
...the constituent dots
are invisible.

597
00:40:09,152 --> 00:40:11,780
We see only
their cumulative effect.

598
00:40:13,023 --> 00:40:16,083
The information specifies
how bright or dark...

599
00:40:16,293 --> 00:40:17,920
...each dot is to be.

600
00:40:18,128 --> 00:40:21,188
After processing, the dots
are stored on a magnetic disk...

601
00:40:21,398 --> 00:40:23,832
...something like a phonograph record.

602
00:40:24,067 --> 00:40:27,901
By this day, there were already 1 1,000
pictures from Voyager 2 in our...

603
00:40:28,105 --> 00:40:29,766
...electronic library.

604
00:40:30,774 --> 00:40:34,505
Finally, the end product
of this remarkable set...

605
00:40:34,711 --> 00:40:36,941
...of links and relays...

606
00:40:38,048 --> 00:40:41,643
...is a hard copy which comes
out of this machine showing...

607
00:40:42,052 --> 00:40:44,987
...in this case,
the wonders of Europa...

608
00:40:45,188 --> 00:40:49,420
...which were recorded for the first
time in human history, today.

609
00:40:49,960 --> 00:40:52,986
It is absolutely astonishing.

610
00:40:53,964 --> 00:40:58,526
Voyager 1 got very good pictures
of the other three big moons...

611
00:40:58,735 --> 00:41:02,102
...Galilean satellites of Jupiter,
but not of Europa.

612
00:41:02,306 --> 00:41:05,241
It was left to Voyager 2 today...

613
00:41:05,442 --> 00:41:08,536
...to get the first
close-up pictures of Europa...

614
00:41:08,745 --> 00:41:12,272
...where we see things that are only
a few kilometers across.

615
00:41:12,482 --> 00:41:15,645
At first glance, it looks like
nothing so much as...

616
00:41:15,852 --> 00:41:20,789
...the canal network of Mars that
Lowell imagined existed on that planet.

617
00:41:21,258 --> 00:41:26,195
We see an amazing, intricate network
of crisscrossing...

618
00:41:26,463 --> 00:41:28,761
...straight and curved lines.

619
00:41:28,966 --> 00:41:31,025
Are these straight lines ridges?

620
00:41:31,234 --> 00:41:32,326
Are they troughs?

621
00:41:32,536 --> 00:41:35,562
Is it connected with plate tectonics
on the Earth?

622
00:41:35,772 --> 00:41:40,072
How does it illuminate the other
satellites of the Jovian system?

623
00:41:40,377 --> 00:41:43,676
At this moment,
the vaunted technology...

624
00:41:43,880 --> 00:41:46,178
...has produced something
astonishing.

625
00:41:46,383 --> 00:41:48,681
But it remains for...

626
00:41:49,186 --> 00:41:53,555
...the limitations and cleverness
of another device...

627
00:41:53,757 --> 00:41:56,692
...the human brain, to figure it out.

628
00:41:58,862 --> 00:42:02,923
Fortunately, we have plenty
of pictures to help us.

629
00:42:03,900 --> 00:42:07,927
What about Gene's idea of geysers
down the troughs?

630
00:42:08,138 --> 00:42:10,265
Geysers down the troughs?

631
00:42:11,475 --> 00:42:13,534
LARR Y SODERBLOM:
You need a mechanism to drive it.

632
00:42:13,744 --> 00:42:17,043
SAGAN:
Larry Soderblom, Voyager imaging team.

633
00:42:17,247 --> 00:42:22,150
LARR Y: An idea was proposed a while
ago that we might have a sort of...

634
00:42:22,352 --> 00:42:24,547
...champagne-bottle model.
And that's...

635
00:42:24,755 --> 00:42:28,088
You seal the crust and have liquid
underneath that solid crust.

636
00:42:28,592 --> 00:42:32,028
Do you have then a condition which
is an explosive effervescence?

637
00:42:32,362 --> 00:42:34,523
SAGAN:
Lonnie Lane, deputy project scientist.

638
00:42:35,799 --> 00:42:39,530
You have enough resolution
in some of these pictures that...

639
00:42:39,736 --> 00:42:42,170
...you don't see anything
spread laterally.

640
00:42:42,372 --> 00:42:45,000
Do we have the high-resolution piece?

641
00:42:45,275 --> 00:42:47,869
-It was right here.
-There it is.

642
00:42:48,078 --> 00:42:51,013
We'll pick out the relief,
and if we're going to see...

643
00:42:51,214 --> 00:42:52,511
...the things we recognize...

644
00:42:52,716 --> 00:42:55,412
SAGAN: Weeks after the pictures
from Europa were received...

645
00:42:55,619 --> 00:42:57,712
...we were still debating
what was in them.

646
00:42:57,921 --> 00:43:00,890
It's as if we almost got to the...

647
00:43:01,725 --> 00:43:03,158
Look at the mesas here.

648
00:43:03,760 --> 00:43:06,923
We almost got the resolution
needed to see the craters.

649
00:43:07,130 --> 00:43:10,566
The craters which would last
indefinitely on a crust this thin.

650
00:43:10,767 --> 00:43:12,291
Apart from the r?seaus...

651
00:43:12,502 --> 00:43:17,337
...there's a set of very fine
small dots, markings...

652
00:43:17,541 --> 00:43:19,736
...mostly in the mottled terrain.

653
00:43:19,943 --> 00:43:23,538
Like those guys. Do you think
those are...

654
00:43:23,747 --> 00:43:27,205
...sites of outgassing, calderas,
fumaroles, solfataras?

655
00:43:27,417 --> 00:43:30,545
I don't know, but I'll tell you
one thing I just found...

656
00:43:32,789 --> 00:43:34,188
Look right here.

657
00:43:35,759 --> 00:43:37,124
It disappeared.

658
00:43:38,228 --> 00:43:40,389
See the central peak?

659
00:43:40,597 --> 00:43:42,497
See the little hole?

660
00:43:45,168 --> 00:43:47,636
I think it's an impact crater.
Look at the central peak.

661
00:43:47,838 --> 00:43:49,931
SAGAN:
There are almost no impact craters.

662
00:43:50,140 --> 00:43:51,767
Wait, we just found one.

663
00:43:51,975 --> 00:43:53,203
Almost none.

664
00:43:54,311 --> 00:43:58,441
Therefore, finding one which is
alleged to be the exception...

665
00:43:58,648 --> 00:44:01,640
...maybe it's not the exception,
but something else.

666
00:44:01,852 --> 00:44:06,016
Perhaps, but you asked about those
little holes that we can't make out.

667
00:44:08,158 --> 00:44:11,525
The big craters go away by some
rheological deformation...

668
00:44:11,728 --> 00:44:14,561
...and the little ones stay
but are out of our resolution.

669
00:44:14,764 --> 00:44:18,666
That's because they're one-tenth
the depth of the rigid crust.

670
00:44:18,869 --> 00:44:20,063
Well, maybe.

671
00:44:21,304 --> 00:44:24,000
SAGAN: Computer processing of
the pictures has revealed...

672
00:44:24,207 --> 00:44:27,438
...a few features on Europa
which seem to be impact craters.

673
00:44:27,644 --> 00:44:28,702
But something...

674
00:44:28,912 --> 00:44:31,210
...has wiped out the big craters.

675
00:44:31,414 --> 00:44:33,746
Computer processing
also played a major role...

676
00:44:33,950 --> 00:44:37,977
...in an amazing Voyager discovery
made on the moon next to Europa...

677
00:44:38,188 --> 00:44:40,952
...a world called lo.

678
00:44:42,492 --> 00:44:45,791
Even from Earth we could tell
that lo had a strange color.

679
00:44:45,996 --> 00:44:49,363
We knew that somehow sulfur
had been removed from its surface...

680
00:44:49,566 --> 00:44:53,229
...and ejected into a great
doughnut of gas orbiting Jupiter.

681
00:44:53,436 --> 00:44:57,304
Then Voyager 1 sailed close to lo.

682
00:44:59,709 --> 00:45:03,941
There were a few places on lo which
looked like the mouths of volcanoes...

683
00:45:04,147 --> 00:45:05,842
...but it was hard to be sure.

684
00:45:06,716 --> 00:45:10,208
Then, Linda Morabito, a member
of the Voyager navigation team...

685
00:45:10,420 --> 00:45:13,287
...used a computer
to enhance the edge of lo...

686
00:45:13,490 --> 00:45:16,015
...in order to bring out
the stars behind.

687
00:45:16,226 --> 00:45:20,128
Four days after the Voyager 1
encounter with Jupiter...

688
00:45:20,330 --> 00:45:24,130
...I was looking at an
optical navigation frame.

689
00:45:24,334 --> 00:45:28,464
In enhancing this particular quadrant,
what became very evident to me...

690
00:45:28,672 --> 00:45:30,731
...was an anomalous crescent...

691
00:45:30,941 --> 00:45:34,308
...in the upper left-hand corner,
just off the limb of lo.

692
00:45:34,511 --> 00:45:35,705
SAGAN:
What was it?

693
00:45:35,912 --> 00:45:38,312
The plume was in exactly
the position...

694
00:45:38,515 --> 00:45:40,540
...of one of the suspected volcanoes.

695
00:45:40,951 --> 00:45:44,352
We realized then that
what we were observing...

696
00:45:44,554 --> 00:45:48,615
...was a volcanic plume and,
in fact, a volcanic eruption.

697
00:45:50,694 --> 00:45:55,393
SAGAN: Voyager had discovered the
first active volcano beyond the Earth.

698
00:45:57,767 --> 00:46:00,201
We then found that lo
has many volcanoes.

699
00:46:00,403 --> 00:46:03,497
There are at least nine
intermittently active plumes...

700
00:46:03,707 --> 00:46:06,335
...and hundreds, maybe thousands,
of extinct ones.

701
00:46:06,543 --> 00:46:10,536
The plumes can eject sulfur
and other atoms off lo altogether...

702
00:46:10,880 --> 00:46:14,441
...and account for the sulfur clouds
surrounding Jupiter.

703
00:46:15,185 --> 00:46:19,952
Rivers of molten sulfur flow down
the sides of the volcanic mountains...

704
00:46:20,156 --> 00:46:23,216
...and are the probable source
of Io's distinctive colors.

705
00:46:23,426 --> 00:46:28,159
The volcanoes may be tapping some vast
underground ocean of liquid sulfur...

706
00:46:28,365 --> 00:46:32,734
...beneath a surface
that is only a few thousand years old.

707
00:46:36,640 --> 00:46:40,098
So far, in our voyages
to the outer solar system...

708
00:46:40,343 --> 00:46:42,811
...we humans have stayed home...

709
00:46:43,013 --> 00:46:46,244
...and sent robots and computers
to explore in our stead.

710
00:46:46,449 --> 00:46:49,509
Someday, perhaps, we'll go ourselves.

711
00:46:50,620 --> 00:46:51,814
But suppose...

712
00:46:52,422 --> 00:46:55,357
...like those Dutch sea captains
of the 1 7th century...

713
00:46:55,558 --> 00:46:58,994
...the computers aboard Voyager
could keep a ship's log.

714
00:46:59,195 --> 00:47:03,291
That log, a combination of the events
of Voyagers 1 and 2...

715
00:47:03,500 --> 00:47:06,367
...might read something like this:

716
00:47:08,805 --> 00:47:13,504
Day 1: After much concern
about provisions and instruments...

717
00:47:13,710 --> 00:47:17,942
...we successfully lift off from
Cape Canaveral on our long journey...

718
00:47:18,148 --> 00:47:20,742
...to the planets and the stars.

719
00:47:29,159 --> 00:47:33,357
Day 13: We have taken the first
photograph of the Earth and moon...

720
00:47:33,563 --> 00:47:37,090
...as worlds together in space.
A pretty pair.

721
00:47:41,104 --> 00:47:44,631
Day 1 70: A problem
in the deployment of the boom...

722
00:47:44,841 --> 00:47:47,139
...that supports
the science scan platform.

723
00:47:47,344 --> 00:47:49,141
If the problem is not solved...

724
00:47:49,346 --> 00:47:51,940
...we will be unable to take
most of our pictures.

725
00:47:56,186 --> 00:48:01,123
Day 207: Boom problem solved, but
failure of main radio transmitter.

726
00:48:01,658 --> 00:48:03,751
If the backup transmitter
also fails...

727
00:48:03,960 --> 00:48:07,225
...no one on Earth
will ever hear from us again.

728
00:48:08,264 --> 00:48:09,458
Day 21 5:

729
00:48:09,666 --> 00:48:11,964
We cross the orbit of Mars...

730
00:48:12,168 --> 00:48:14,295
...and enter the main asteroid belt.

731
00:48:15,905 --> 00:48:20,171
Day 570: We can now make out
finer detail on Jupiter...

732
00:48:20,377 --> 00:48:24,040
...than the largest telescopes
on Earth have ever obtained.

733
00:48:29,052 --> 00:48:30,679
Day 640:

734
00:48:30,887 --> 00:48:34,618
The cloud patterns are distinctive
and gorgeous.

735
00:48:34,824 --> 00:48:36,451
No painter trapped on Earth...

736
00:48:36,659 --> 00:48:39,457
...ever imagined a world
so strange and lovely.

737
00:48:42,699 --> 00:48:46,226
The white clouds are ammonia
crystals, high and cold.

738
00:48:46,436 --> 00:48:49,166
We do not know the nature
of the red-brown clouds.

739
00:48:49,372 --> 00:48:51,966
Maybe phosphorous or sulfur
as a stain.

740
00:48:52,175 --> 00:48:56,612
Perhaps organic molecules of the sort
that led, four billion years ago...

741
00:48:56,813 --> 00:48:59,680
...back on Earth,
to the origin of life.

742
00:48:59,883 --> 00:49:02,579
And what is the great red spot?

743
00:49:03,086 --> 00:49:04,075
(COMPUTER HUMS)

744
00:49:05,355 --> 00:49:08,449
It is an immense swirling column
of gas...

745
00:49:08,658 --> 00:49:10,853
...reaching high above adjacent
clouds.

746
00:49:11,060 --> 00:49:13,893
So large that it could hold
half a dozen Earths.

747
00:49:14,097 --> 00:49:17,533
Its motion hypnotizes us.

748
00:49:21,304 --> 00:49:25,104
Some think that the red spot
is a great spinning storm...

749
00:49:25,308 --> 00:49:27,674
...a million years old.

750
00:49:30,914 --> 00:49:35,851
Day 650: Encounter.
A day of wonders.

751
00:49:39,055 --> 00:49:41,148
The ship maneuvers
so we can take pictures...

752
00:49:41,357 --> 00:49:43,985
...of the multi-ringed basin
on Callisto.

753
00:49:48,965 --> 00:49:53,493
Images of the astonishing
lined surface of Ganymede.

754
00:49:58,074 --> 00:50:00,804
A close passage by Europa.

755
00:50:03,179 --> 00:50:05,647
And, a view of volcanic lo.

756
00:50:09,419 --> 00:50:12,855
We successfully negotiate
the treacherous radiation belts...

757
00:50:13,056 --> 00:50:16,492
...and accomplish
the ring plane crossing.

758
00:50:17,627 --> 00:50:20,095
Looking back, we marvel
at the rings...

759
00:50:20,296 --> 00:50:25,063
...and see the sun emerge
from behind the giant planet.

760
00:50:30,039 --> 00:50:34,976
We are outward bound on our mission
to explore the outer solar system.

761
00:50:35,879 --> 00:50:37,870
Ten thousand years from now...

762
00:50:38,081 --> 00:50:41,608
...Voyager will plunge onward
to the stars.

763
00:50:42,752 --> 00:50:47,382
We have made the ships
that sail the sea of space.

764
00:50:51,261 --> 00:50:52,888
We travel past Jupiter...

765
00:50:53,096 --> 00:50:56,395
...three quarters of a billion
kilometers from the sun...

766
00:50:56,933 --> 00:50:59,959
...Saturn, one and a half billion,
Uranus, three billion...

767
00:51:00,169 --> 00:51:04,799
...and Neptune, four and a half
billion kilometers away.

768
00:51:07,877 --> 00:51:09,276
In our ship of the mind...

769
00:51:09,479 --> 00:51:13,745
...we retrace the itinerary
of the two Voyager spacecraft...

770
00:51:13,950 --> 00:51:17,647
...on their journeys to Saturn
and beyond.

771
00:51:19,722 --> 00:51:22,987
Saturn was first glimpsed
through the telescope by Galileo.

772
00:51:23,192 --> 00:51:26,127
Its rings first understood by Huygens.

773
00:51:26,329 --> 00:51:30,698
But only now do we begin to penetrate
its deeper mysteries.

774
00:51:36,673 --> 00:51:40,575
Saturn is the second largest planet
in the solar system.

775
00:51:41,444 --> 00:51:45,676
Like Jupiter, it is cloud-covered,
and rotates once every 10 hours.

776
00:51:45,882 --> 00:51:49,215
It has a weaker magnetic field,
a weaker radiation belt...

777
00:51:49,419 --> 00:51:51,683
...and a grand, magnificent...

778
00:51:51,888 --> 00:51:55,085
...exquisite system of rings.

779
00:51:56,793 --> 00:51:59,557
The rings are composed of billions
of tiny moons...

780
00:51:59,762 --> 00:52:02,560
...each circling Saturn
in its own orbit.

781
00:52:03,266 --> 00:52:07,498
The biggest gap in the rings
is called the Cassini Division...

782
00:52:07,704 --> 00:52:10,798
...after the colleague of Huygens
who first discovered it.

783
00:52:11,741 --> 00:52:13,299
There are many other gaps...

784
00:52:13,509 --> 00:52:16,535
...each produced by the periodic
gravitational tugs...

785
00:52:16,746 --> 00:52:18,737
...of one of the larger outer moons.

786
00:52:35,865 --> 00:52:38,356
From just beneath the ring plane...

787
00:52:38,568 --> 00:52:42,231
...we see a sky full of moons.

788
00:53:02,058 --> 00:53:06,654
Within the rings,
the individual moons become visible.

789
00:53:08,531 --> 00:53:12,092
They are orbiting chunks
of snow and ice...

790
00:53:13,436 --> 00:53:15,802
...each perhaps a meter across.

791
00:53:21,344 --> 00:53:24,939
In young parts of the ring system,
there hasn't been enough time...

792
00:53:25,148 --> 00:53:29,517
...for collisions to round the edges
of these fragments...

793
00:53:29,719 --> 00:53:32,210
...the snowballs of Saturn.

794
00:54:18,234 --> 00:54:23,001
Far from the rings,
bathed in its red light...

795
00:54:24,307 --> 00:54:28,073
...we encounter Saturn's immense
cloud-covered moon...

796
00:54:28,277 --> 00:54:29,505
...Titan.

797
00:54:42,458 --> 00:54:44,892
It has an atmosphere
denser than that of Mars...

798
00:54:45,695 --> 00:54:47,526
...and a thick layer of red clouds...

799
00:54:47,730 --> 00:54:51,291
...which are probably composed
of complex organic molecules...

800
00:54:51,501 --> 00:54:55,164
...produced by solar ultraviolet light
and other energy sources...

801
00:54:55,371 --> 00:54:57,066
...from the methane-rich air.

802
00:55:04,413 --> 00:55:07,678
No ship from Earth
has ever penetrated those clouds...

803
00:55:07,884 --> 00:55:12,446
...and viewed, close-up,
the surface of this tantalizing world.

804
00:55:18,795 --> 00:55:22,162
It seems likely that the ground
is covered, encrusted...

805
00:55:22,365 --> 00:55:26,426
...with organic molecules
raining from the sky.

806
00:55:32,408 --> 00:55:36,708
There may be volcanoes
and valleys of ice...

807
00:55:36,913 --> 00:55:39,711
...and, just perhaps...

808
00:55:39,916 --> 00:55:44,785
...hiding in the warm places,
some very different kind of life.

809
00:55:52,862 --> 00:55:54,921
Near an ice cliff of Titan...

810
00:55:55,131 --> 00:55:58,498
...through a rare break
in the clouds of organic molecules...

811
00:55:58,701 --> 00:56:03,536
...we can see, looming and lovely,
the ringed planet, Saturn.

812
00:56:05,007 --> 00:56:09,341
It is a view that will still be
appreciated centuries from now...

813
00:56:09,579 --> 00:56:11,740
...by our descendants,
who will know it well.

814
00:56:11,948 --> 00:56:14,348
As well as we have come to know...

815
00:56:14,550 --> 00:56:17,883
...Hudson's Bay and the Barents Sea...

816
00:56:18,087 --> 00:56:22,080
...Indonesia, and Australia
and New York.

817
00:56:22,925 --> 00:56:27,521
They will look back to when Titan was
first seen by Voyager spaceships...

818
00:56:27,730 --> 00:56:30,893
...on their epic journeys
past the giant planets...

819
00:56:31,100 --> 00:56:32,795
...out of the solar system...

820
00:56:33,002 --> 00:56:36,802
...to the great dark
between the stars.

821
00:56:54,257 --> 00:56:56,282
Since Cosmos was first shown...

822
00:56:56,492 --> 00:57:00,394
...Voyager spacecraft have explored
the systems of the planets...

823
00:57:00,596 --> 00:57:03,360
...Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune...

824
00:57:03,566 --> 00:57:08,435
...and have now passed the outermost
planets on their way to the stars.

825
00:57:08,871 --> 00:57:12,568
We inserted the flavor of those
encounters in our captain's log.

826
00:57:13,342 --> 00:57:15,367
But with image processing...

827
00:57:15,578 --> 00:57:19,810
...we've been able to reconstruct
astonishing movies...

828
00:57:20,082 --> 00:57:21,743
...of some of these worlds.

829
00:57:21,951 --> 00:57:25,352
Here, for example, is Jupiter,
with its great red spot.

830
00:57:26,923 --> 00:57:30,188
And volcanic lo, spinning before us.

831
00:57:31,193 --> 00:57:36,130
Icy Enceladus, a tiny moon of Saturn,
on much of which, somehow...

832
00:57:36,599 --> 00:57:38,533
...the craters have melted.

833
00:57:39,735 --> 00:57:42,101
And Miranda, of Uranus.

834
00:57:43,639 --> 00:57:46,369
Austere, blue Neptune.

835
00:57:48,711 --> 00:57:52,112
Or consider Titan,
the giant moon of Saturn.

836
00:57:52,315 --> 00:57:55,682
We've taken the nitrogen and methane
in its atmosphere...

837
00:57:55,885 --> 00:57:59,377
...irradiated it in the lab with
electrons of the sort that are...

838
00:57:59,588 --> 00:58:02,250
...beamed at Titan from
Saturn's magnetic field...

839
00:58:02,458 --> 00:58:05,154
...and we made this stuff...

840
00:58:05,761 --> 00:58:10,198
...which matches, almost perfectly, the
observed properties of the Titan haze.

841
00:58:10,399 --> 00:58:11,491
What is it?

842
00:58:11,701 --> 00:58:14,135
It's a mixture of
complex organic molecules.

843
00:58:14,337 --> 00:58:17,534
You drop some into water and,
among other things, you make...

844
00:58:17,740 --> 00:58:20,334
...amino acids,
the building blocks of proteins.

845
00:58:20,543 --> 00:58:23,478
So the starting materials of life...

846
00:58:23,679 --> 00:58:27,877
...are raining from the skies
of Titan, like manna from heaven.

847
00:58:28,084 --> 00:58:30,746
I can't wait
until the Cassini mission...

848
00:58:30,953 --> 00:58:35,219
...sends an entry probe
through the organic haze of Titan...

849
00:58:35,424 --> 00:58:37,551
...to its enigmatic surface.

850
00:58:37,960 --> 00:58:42,897
The Voyager spacecraft rush on
past the planets and to the stars...

851
00:58:43,132 --> 00:58:45,259
...still returning data.

852
00:58:45,801 --> 00:58:48,463
As it left the planetary part
of the solar system...

853
00:58:48,671 --> 00:58:50,935
...Voyager 1 turned back...

854
00:58:51,140 --> 00:58:55,008
...to take one last portrait
of the planets of the solar system.

855
00:58:55,678 --> 00:58:58,613
...and one of those pictures
was of the Earth.

856
00:58:58,814 --> 00:59:03,251
A tiny blue dot, set in a sunbeam.

857
00:59:03,886 --> 00:59:05,217
Here it is.

858
00:59:05,421 --> 00:59:07,946
That's where we live. That's home.

859
00:59:08,157 --> 00:59:12,025
We humans are one species,
and this is our world.

860
00:59:12,528 --> 00:59:14,860
It is our responsibility
to cherish it.

861
00:59:15,064 --> 00:59:19,023
Of all the worlds in our solar system,
the only one, so far as we know...

862
00:59:19,235 --> 00:59:21,135
...graced by life.

